[
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "In our family and friends, my mom is renowned to be one of the best biryani chef’s. This is an impressive feat as us Pakistani’s have huge families and even more family friends. While cooking is traditonally known as a “girls activity” among Pakistani’s, I have an immense curiosity to learn things especially when it comes to “making”. Due to this, I had started cooking from a very young age. Starting off with simple things like eggs and moving onto more difficult dishes like Hakka chili chicken and different types of Pakistani curries. ",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "As no one else in my family has any interest in cooking, I have become the legacy chef in our family. This biryani recipe was the start to my journey as the next Ahmed chef.",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "heading_2",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "Why hasn’t anyone else learned this recipe?",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "heading_3",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "Nobody cares",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "First and foremost, because nobody else really cares. Everyone thinks my mom will keep cooking and when she stops, we’ll just eat biryani made by someone else (wives, sisters etc. since only women are allowed to cook, obviously). However, to me, my mother’s specific recipe is so delicious that I felt the need that it has to be passed down and become a legacy for our family. ",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "heading_3",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "Nobody can cook",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "Secondly, I am the only person in our family who has taken any real interest in cooking. My sister is basically allergic to the kitchen (quite ironic for a traditional Pakistani household) and my brother can cook to survive as he lived alone for university, however, he doesn’t have any particular interest in it to learn exquisite dishes. My father falls in the same category as my brother. Therefore, I am the only one who learned how to actually cook and took interest to it for reasons mentioned above. ",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "heading_3",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "The recipe isn’t a recipe",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "Thirdly, as most Pakistani mother’s (and chef’s in general), my mother doesn’t cook through “recipes”. She doesn’t have a set formula to cook biryani, she doesn’t measure out ingredients and she doesn’t even know what most ingredients are called (in English atleast). For this reason, in order to learn how to make her biryani, you would have to cook it with her a few times and learn by doing. Without interest in cooking or learning how to make the dish, nobody has time for that.",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "heading_2",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "What did I do?",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "As I mentioned, the only way to learn this “recipe” is by doing and repetition. However, I wanted to try and change that. I learned through asking my mom to show me how to make the biryani and spending the hours required with her, watching how it’s made and asking questions. After this, I asked her to let me make it and to be on stand-by with me to correct any mistakes. Once I had done this, I was confident in making it on my own and was able to do so. ",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "content": [
      {
        "plainText": "What I did differently throughout this process was document all the steps, ingredients and quantities to the best of my ability. As with any complex dish, a recipe will never do you justice as you have to learn what we call ",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      },
      {
        "plainText": "andaza ",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": true,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      },
      {
        "plainText": "in Urdu. This roughly translates to “rough estimation” and in a cooking context it means the ability to know, through experience; the quantities of ingredients, cooking time etc. This documentation serves as a way for this recipe to be passed down more easily, however, it will never be as it should be unless taught by someone who was taught by someone else back to my mother. The chain probably goes back even further to my grandmother and to her mother etc. I’ll probably be the first father/brother/husband on this chain which is exciting. ",
        "annotations": {
          "bold": false,
          "italic": false,
          "strikethrough": false,
          "underline": false,
          "code": false,
          "color": "default"
        }
      }
